For anyone who was fooled by the trailer or other ads, this was produced by Todd Phillips (producer, director, writer of Old School, Due Date, and the Hangover movies) not directed by him. Nima Nourizadeh directed Project X and it is his first feature film. Up until this point he directed nothing but music videos and advertisements. I'm not trying to sway anyone away from watching this but I was just kinda irked by how they advertised this movie making it seem like Mr. Well-Known Todd Phillips directed it when all he did was write some checks. I understand that Hollywood loves to mislead people into watching their films but here it doesn't matter really because it's FREE! FU HOLLYWOOD! Thanks again EZ.

ok for those of you that dont know EASY CINAVIA BYPASS FOR PS3. Cinavia uses a digital timestamp to cut sound about 20 to 30 min into playback. An easy way to bypass this is when your ps3 stops playing sound immediatley pause your movie. Then go into your system settings under date/time. Move your ps3 timeclock forward 1 hour. Then go back to your movie and hit resume and you will have sound again for another 30 min because cinavia uses the ps3's clock for the timestamp so when you change the clock it resets the timestamp. Granted you have to do it 3 or 4 times its the best and easiest way to bypass other than completely re-encoding your movie. I hope this helps guys.

(VERY LOOSELY BASED ON A FEW ACTUAL EVENTS AT BEST) 

Producer Todd Phillips described the film's conception as an experiment, after executive producer Alex Heineman provided a basic concept, with the production team sharing tales of memorable parties that they had either attended or heard about.

 Writer Michael Bacall developed these stories into an outline scenario in one night with the goal of creating the "gnarliest high school party of all time". The remainder of the story was fleshed out in the following weeks.

To create the impression that the events of Project X had actually happened, the producers decided against casting known faces, but to find completely new actors. 

Phillips stated that the goal of the open call was to cast “unknown actors" and "real people of all ethnicities,” who would not normally be given a chance to star in a film.
